Connect1-Stigma: 2. Net Reclassification Index

Net Reclassification Index

Method

In the Net Reclassification Index procedure, each novel predictor is added to a base regression model one at a time, to see if the new model with the additional predictor correctly classifies more cases than the original base model. If the new model has an improved classification rate (net of any newly misclassified cases), the additional predictor is assumed to be helpful. No more than one additional predictor is tested at a time. Any helpful predictors are then added to the base predictors in a final logistic regression model.

The participants in this analysis were n=753 who have a four-frequency PTA of > 25 dB HL in their better ear and no missing data in 28 predictor variables and 1 outcome variable. As before, the data were split into 7 folds, and the NRI procedure was conducted on subsets of the data to get an idea of the robustness of predictors. I chose Age and HHIE to be predictors in the base model, as they were both robust predictors in the previous logistic regression analysis, and they are less interesting than the novel social predictors. After the procedure was performed on subsets of the data, a final procedure was also performed with the full data.

Results

There were no novel predictors that consistently improved classification across different subsets of the data. At most, a novel predictor improved classification by about 4 percentage points in a particular subset of data, i.e., a really small and inconsistent effect. The base model itself had an accuracy of 64% across the full dataset, with a sensitivity of 60% and specificity of 65%.

Conclusion

Age and HHIE are robust predictors of hearing aid purchase in the base model across different subsets of the data. However, none of the other 26 “novel” predictors improved model classification performance.
